   7 class ValidationError(ValueError):
   8     def __init__(self, value, validator):
   9         super(ValidationError, self).__init__(value)
  10         self.validator = validator
  11         self.value = value
  12 
  13     def __str__(self):
  14         return '{}\n{}'.format(
  15             self.value,
  16             '\n'.join(
  17                 '{}: {}'.format(k, e)
  18                 for k, errors in self.validator.errors.items()
  19                 for e in errors
  20             )
  21         )
  22 
  23 
  24 VALIDATORS = {}
  25 
  26 
  27 def validate(cls, data):
  28     if not cerberus:  # Skip validation if Cerberus is not available.
  29         return
  30     schema = cls.__SCHEMA__
  31     key = id(schema)
  32     try:
  33         v = VALIDATORS[key]
  34     except KeyError:
  35         v = VALIDATORS[key] = cerberus.Validator(schema, allow_unknown=True)
  36     if v.validate(data, normalize=False):
  37         return
  38     raise ValidationError(data, v)

  41 class DataView(object):
  42     """A "view" to a data.
  43 
  44     Validates the input mapping on creation. A subclass is expected to
  45     provide a `__SCHEMA__` class attribute specifying a validator schema.
  46     """
  47 
  48     def __init__(self, data):
  49         self.validate(data)
  50         self._data = data
  51 
  52     def __repr__(self):
  53         return "{0}({1!r})".format(type(self).__name__, self._data)
  54 
  55     def __eq__(self, other):
  56         if not isinstance(other, type(self)):
  57             raise TypeError(
  58                 "cannot compare {0!r} with {1!r}".format(
  59                     type(self).__name__, type(other).__name__
  60                 )
  61             )
  62         return self._data == other._data
  63 
  64     def __getitem__(self, key):
  65         return self._data[key]
  66 
  67     def __setitem__(self, key, value):
  68         self._data[key] = value
  69 
  70     def __delitem__(self, key):
  71         del self._data[key]
  72 
  73     def get(self, key, default=None):
  74         try:
  75             return self[key]
  76         except KeyError:
  77             return default
  78 
  79     @classmethod
  80     def validate(cls, data):
  81         return validate(cls, data)
  82

  84 class DataViewCollection(DataView):
  85     """A homogeneous collection of data views.
  86 
  87     Subclasses are expected to assign a class attribute `item_class` to specify
  88     the type of items it contains. This class will be used to coerce return
  89     values when accessed. The item class should conform to the `DataView`
  90     protocol.
  91 
  92     You should not instantiate an instance from this class, but from one of its
  93     subclasses instead.
  94     """
  95 
  96     item_class = None
  97 
  98     def __repr__(self):
  99         return "{0}({1!r})".format(type(self).__name__, self._data)
 100 
 101     def __len__(self):
 102         return len(self._data)
 103 
 104     def __getitem__(self, key):
 105         return self.item_class(self._data[key])
 106 
 107     def __setitem__(self, key, value):
 108         if isinstance(value, DataView):
 109             value = value._data
 110         self._data[key] = value
 111 
 112     def __delitem__(self, key):
 113         del self._data[key]
 114 
 115 
 116 class DataViewMapping(DataViewCollection):
 117     """A mapping of data views.
 118 
 119     The keys are primitive values, while values are instances of `item_class`.
 120     """
 121 
 122     @classmethod
 123     def validate(cls, data):
 124         for d in data.values():
 125             cls.item_class.validate(d)
 126 
 127     def __iter__(self):
 128         return iter(self._data)
 129 
 130     def keys(self):
 131         return self._data.keys()
 132 
 133     def values(self):
 134         return [self[k] for k in self._data]
 135 
 136     def items(self):
 137         return [(k, self[k]) for k in self._data]
 138 
 139 
 140 class DataViewSequence(DataViewCollection):
 141     """A sequence of data views.
 142 
 143     Each entry is an instance of `item_class`.
 144     """
 145 
 146     @classmethod
 147     def validate(cls, data):
 148         for d in data:
 149             cls.item_class.validate(d)
 150 
 151     def __iter__(self):
 152         return (self.item_class(d) for d in self._data)
 153 
 154     def __getitem__(self, key):
 155         if isinstance(key, slice):
 156             return type(self)(self._data[key])
 157         return super(DataViewSequence, self).__getitem__(key)
 158 
 159     def append(self, value):
 160         if isinstance(value, DataView):
 161             value = value._data
 162         self._data.append(value)
